WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Ryan (Sales): Thanks everyone for joining. Today is our technical and compliance deep dive, so I've brought Priya from Solutions Engineering and our security team lead, David.

2
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
James (IT Director): Appreciate that. I'm James, IT Director at Hartwell Group. And I've got Karen from our legal team and Dev, our CISO, also on the call.

3
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Dev (CISO): Yeah, Dev here. I'll be asking the uncomfortable security questions so, uh, apologies in advance.

4
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Ha, please do. That's exactly why I'm here. No uncomfortable questions in, um, my experience, only uncomfortable answers if you're hiding something, which we're not.

5
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Karen (Legal): And I'll be focused on the contractual side, the DPA, MSA terms, and, uh, the data portability clauses specifically.

6
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Ryan (Sales): Perfect. Let me suggest we, um, work through this in three blocks: infrastructure and architecture, security and compliance, then legal and contractual. Does that work for everyone?

7
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
James (IT Director): That works. Let me start with infrastructure. We're a UK-headquartered company with EMEA operations. Where is our data actually stored?

8
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:45.000
David (NovaPulse Security): For UK and EU customers, your data is stored in the EU Central region on AWS, specifically Frankfurt, Germany, by default. We also have a UK option if you prefer, and EU to EU disaster recovery only.

9
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:51.000
James (IT Director): So our data never leaves the EU jurisdiction for any reason?

10
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Correct. Cross-region replication for disaster recovery happens only within the same regulatory jurisdiction. EU stays EU. We don't replicate EU data to US East or any non-EU region without, uh, explicit customer authorisation.

11
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Dev (CISO): What's the hosting model? Multi-tenant or can we get dedicated infrastructure?

12
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:11.000
David (NovaPulse Security): By default on Business plan you're on multi-tenant SaaS. Logical data isolation at the application and database layers. Enterprise plan gives you single-tenant dedicated cloud, physically separate infrastructure. And for, uh, the highest sovereignty requirement we also have a self-hosted option.

13
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Dev (CISO): We're not air-gapped so multi-tenant is fine as long as the isolation is robust. What does logical isolation actually mean technically?

14
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:24.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Every tenant's data is partitioned at the application layer with tenant ID-scoped queries, and at the database layer with row-level security enforced by PostgreSQL's RLS policies. A query from your tenant context, um, cannot access another tenant's rows even if someone found a way to bypass the application layer.

15
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Dev (CISO): What's the maximum concurrent user limit before we'd need dedicated infra?

16
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Priya (Solutions Eng): Five hundred concurrent active sessions on multi-tenant. At your current projected headcount of 220 users you're well within that. If you ever approach the threshold we proactively migrate you to dedicated, which, uh, scales to five thousand plus concurrent users.

17
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:42.000
James (IT Director): What's the self-hosted minimum spec if we ever wanted to go down that route?

18
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Priya (Solutions Eng): For a production self-hosted deployment we'd recommend 32 GB RAM per application node, 16 vCPUs, 100 GB SSD, on Ubuntu 22.04 LTS, orchestrated by Kubernetes 1.27 or above. Database node, PostgreSQL 15 plus, separate 32 GB RAM and 500 GB SSD minimum.

19
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
James (IT Director): And for high availability, like a proper HA cluster?

20
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Priya (Solutions Eng): Three-node application cluster, 64 GB RAM per node, same vCPU spec, NVMe storage preferred. Database primary with streaming replica. A standard three-node cluster handles around, um, 1500 concurrent users comfortably. Full specs are in the deployment guide.

21
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Dev (CISO): Let's move to encryption. How is data encrypted at rest and who manages the keys?

22
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:15.000
David (NovaPulse Security): All data at rest is encrypted with AES-256-GCM. Keys are managed via AWS KMS with automatic rotation every 365 days by default. On Enterprise plans you can configure 90-day rotation.

23
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Dev (CISO): Can we manage our own keys? We have a strict policy that sensitive data keys should not be held by the vendor.

24
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:28.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Yes, that's exactly what BYOK gives you. Available on Enterprise. You integrate your own KMS, whether that's HashiCorp Vault, your own AWS KMS, Azure Key Vault, or Google Cloud KMS, and we never hold a copy of your encryption keys.

25
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Dev (CISO): So if a NovaPulse engineer needed to troubleshoot our database, could they see our data?

26
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:42.000
David (NovaPulse Security): No. Even without BYOK, sensitive fields have an additional field-level encryption layer at the application tier. A support engineer with database access would see AES ciphertext, not readable values. With BYOK on Enterprise, the decryption requires a live call to your own KMS, which creates an audit event in your key management system. So you'd, um, see any access attempt independently.

27
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Dev (CISO): What about data in transit?

28
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.000
David (NovaPulse Security): TLS 1.2 minimum, TLS 1.3 enforced by default on all new tenant configurations. All traffic between client, whether browser, mobile app, or API, and the platform goes over TLS.

29
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Dev (CISO): What certifications do you hold? I need specifics, not, uh, marketing language.

30
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:08.000
David (NovaPulse Security): SOC 2 Type II, most recent report covering the period April 2024 to March 2025, renewed annually. ISO 27001 colon 2022, issued January 2025. GDPR Article 28 DPA compliance. EU US Data Privacy Framework listed. HIPAA BAA available for healthcare customers on Business and Enterprise.

31
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Dev (CISO): The difference between SOC 2 Type I and Type II matters to us. Can you explain it?

32
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:21.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Type I is a point-in-time assessment confirming controls were appropriately designed at the audit date. Type II covers an extended period, typically 6 to 12 months, and confirms those controls were continuously operative and effective throughout. It's, uh, the difference between checking that a fire suppression system was installed correctly versus checking it actually worked every day for a year.

33
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Dev (CISO): Good. Can we get a copy of the Type II report?

34
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Yes, available under NDA for qualified prospects. I'll send that alongside the ISO 27001 certificate and the penetration test executive summary from our most recent third-party assessment.

35
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Dev (CISO): Who does your pen testing?

36
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:45.000
David (NovaPulse Security): We use an independent CREST-accredited firm, annual testing on the full platform scope. We also run, um, a continuous bug bounty programme. I can share the scope and recent findings summary under NDA.

37
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Dev (CISO): Okay. What's the access control model? We have complex permissions requirements.

38
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:58.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Role-based access control across all modules with attribute-based extensions on Enterprise. On Enterprise you can restrict data visibility by attributes like, uh, department or region without creating a separate role per organisational unit. SCIM 2.0 for automated provisioning and de-provisioning tied to your identity provider.

39
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
James (IT Director): What identity providers do you support for SSO?

40
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Priya (Solutions Eng): SAML 2.0 and OIDC, compatible with any standards-compliant IdP. Okta, Azure AD, Ping Identity, Google Workspace. Enterprise supports up to five simultaneous IdP connections, useful if you have a post-merger environment.

41
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
James (IT Director): We use Azure AD. Is there, like, any gotcha in that integration?

42
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.000
Priya (Solutions Eng): None at all, it's one of the most common integrations we configure. Standard SAML or OIDC setup, SCIM for auto-provisioning, typically takes an hour to, um, configure during onboarding.

43
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Karen (Legal): Can I jump in on the legal side now? First question, what's the notice period to terminate a contract?

44
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Ryan (Sales): Annual contracts require 60 days notice before the renewal date. If notice isn't given within that window the contract auto-renews for 12 months. Multi-year Enterprise contracts require 90 days.

45
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Karen (Legal): And termination for cause?

46
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Ryan (Sales): Either party can terminate immediately on written notice if the other party materially breaches the agreement and fails to cure within 30 days of receiving written notice of the breach. Notice goes to legal at novapulse.io.

47
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Karen (Legal): Does the MSA include an IP indemnification clause? We've had a vendor try to, um, foist all IP liability onto us before.

48
00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Ryan (Sales): Yes, mutual indemnification. Under Section 12.1 of the standard MSA, NovaPulse defends and indemnifies the customer against third-party claims that the platform infringes a patent, copyright, trademark, or trade secret, as long as the customer notifies us promptly and grants us control of the defence.

49
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Karen (Legal): What's excluded from the indemnity?

50
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Ryan (Sales): Three exclusions under Section 12.3: claims arising from customer-created content, third-party integrations configured by the customer, and modifications to the platform made without NovaPulse authorisation. Those are pretty standard carve-outs.

51
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Karen (Legal): What's the liability cap?

52
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Ryan (Sales): Standard MSA caps indemnity liability at 12 months of fees paid. Enterprise customers can negotiate higher caps, and our, uh, legal team is open to that discussion.

53
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Karen (Legal): We'll want to negotiate that. Now the GDPR question. We process EU employee and customer data. How does the DPA work?

54
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:39.000
David (NovaPulse Security): A GDPR Article 28 compliant DPA is included as a standard exhibit in all MSAs at no cost. NovaPulse acts as Data Processor, you remain the Data Controller. Sub-processors are disclosed at privacy.novapulse.io with 30 days advance written notice of any changes.

55
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Karen (Legal): Can we request a custom DPA? We have specific clauses our Data Protection Officer requires.

56
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Yes. Custom DPAs are reviewed by our legal team. Typically adds two to four weeks to the deal cycle. On Business and Enterprise plans the legal review fee is waived. You'd initiate by emailing legal at novapulse.io with the subject line, Custom DPA Request, and your company name.

57
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Karen (Legal): Good. Now, what happens to our data if we terminate the contract?

58
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:05.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Customers have 30 days post-termination to export all data via the Admin Console or API in CSV, JSON, and Parquet formats, completely free, no per-gigabyte charges. After that window, production data is permanently deleted within 14 days and backup data within 90 days.

59
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Karen (Legal): We need written confirmation of deletion. Is that available?

60
00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:16.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Yes, a deletion confirmation certificate is available on request. We'll send it automatically once the deletion process is complete.

61
00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Dev (CISO): What's your incident response policy? If there's a breach, how quickly do we get notified?

62
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:29.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Our incident response plan requires notification to affected customers within 72 hours of a confirmed breach, which is in line with GDPR Article 33 requirements. We have a dedicated security incident response team on-call 24/7.

63
00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:35.000
Dev (CISO): What's covered in the notification? I've seen vendors send, like, a vague one-liner that satisfies the legal obligation but tells you nothing useful.

64
00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:43.000
David (NovaPulse Security): The notification will include: the nature of the incident, the categories of data affected, the estimated number of records involved, likely consequences of the breach, and the measures we have taken or propose to take. We also assign a named contact from our security team for your DPO to liaise with throughout the response.

65
00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:49.000
Dev (CISO): That's actually a solid answer. One more thing. What's the SLA if there's a P1 critical incident? We can't have our BI platform down during, like, peak trading periods.

66
00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Ryan (Sales): On the Business plan, P1 response is two hours, 24/7. On Enterprise it's one hour, 24/7, with a named Technical Account Manager as your escalation contact. Uptime on Business is guaranteed at 99.95 percent monthly.

67
00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:02.000
Dev (CISO): 99.95 means about 21 minutes of allowable downtime per month. What happens if you breach that?

68
00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Ryan (Sales): SLA credits apply. Ten percent credit if uptime falls below 99.9 percent, 25 percent credit below 99.5 percent, 50 percent credit below 99 percent. Applied to the next invoice.

69
00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Karen (Legal): Are those credits the sole remedy or can we claim consequential damages?

70
00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Ryan (Sales): Under the standard MSA, credits are the sole contractual remedy for uptime failures. Consequential damages are excluded in the standard terms, but, uh, this is one of the clauses Enterprise customers often negotiate. We can discuss it.

71
00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Karen (Legal): We'll want to explore that. Okay I think we have enough to start the MSA redline process. When can we get a draft?

72
00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Ryan (Sales): I'll get a draft MSA out to you by end of week. I'll also include the SOC 2 Type II report under a standard NDA, the ISO 27001 certificate, and the pen test executive summary for Dev's team.

73
00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:38.000
James (IT Director): One last thing. What does the onboarding for our IT team look like? Like, who configures the Azure AD integration and sets up the SCIM provisioning?

74
00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:45.000
Priya (Solutions Eng): Your IT admin and our Implementation Specialist work through it together in the first week of onboarding. We have a step-by-step Azure AD setup guide and we've done this, uh, hundreds of times. Typically it's one to two hours of your IT admin's time.

75
00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:51.000
James (IT Director): That's reassuringly quick. Okay, I think we're good. This has been, um, one of the more technically honest vendor calls I've been on.

76
00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:57.000
Dev (CISO): Agreed. David, you answered the hard questions without ducking them. That's, like, noted.

77
00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:03.000
David (NovaPulse Security): Appreciate that. We'd rather you find out everything now than be surprised later. That's, uh, just how we operate.

78
00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:09.000
Ryan (Sales): Thank you all. Karen I'll follow up on the MSA. Dev I'll get the security pack out. James, Priya will send over the deployment spec sheet. Looking forward to, um, moving this forward.

79
00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Karen (Legal): Thanks everyone. We'll aim to have the MSA redline back within two weeks.

80
00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
James (IT Director): Thanks all. Good call.
